bug.short_desc: SWT-components on different computers with different behaviour

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 86391 Screenshots of working and not working RCP-client
Build ID: I20071213-1700
Steps To Reproduce: On my computer I have finished developing my app as RCP. Launching the app, the app looks like I would expect. Exporting the RCP and launching on my computer works fine and the app looks like it should.
Copying the same directory on another computer, where no Eclipse is installed makes the RCP look like :( Missing Button-Texts, Toolbar-Items are raised instead of flat, Tab-Style works in one View, while in another not, etc.etc.
Since both machines are the same Win XP AND the same Java version (1.6.03) I have no clue, where the difference arise. In the working environment, no path or anything is set in the environment which gives a clue of Eclipse. As well I can launch the app from any kind of directory (e.g. remote-dir) with all the time the same result.
I guess there is some exception on the widgets happening, but don't know how to trace them. Working with previous versions does not make any kind of difference.
Is there any activity for this?

The only difference I can think of is that one machine is using the XP theme and the other, the classic theme.
The missing text comes from the fact that buttons are sometimes unable to display both text and an image at the same time. The rest seems to be the correct look and feel for the classic theme on XP.

Please enter a bug report for the missing text. In the mean time, if you change your code to set the text last, then it will override the image (not great, but your users will be able to read the button).

You are right about the Theme-setting.
The Text is now there, using one of the latest version of Eclipse.
What makes me little bit thinking is, that the Toolbar-Option FLAT makes in the one Theme a different then in the other. AND I have really problems to check, what is the Standard XP handling for Toolbar, cause e.g. in Firefox everything is FLAT as well in Outlook. Even in Eclipse the Toolbar, everything is FLAT.
The read-only Text with the Border is somehow similar. Cause I have troubles to find them in the same Theme with other Applications as BLEVEL resp. sunk. Same applies to the TabFolder.
The ToolBar-issue could be handled with an additional option, while the RO-Text and TabFolder not. But it is hard for a Programmer to think about the Toolbar could look different and could check it.
Investigate SWT.FLAT. It will make the tool bar flat on every platform, including Windows (when possible).

Thx for the hint. Already figured as mentioned.
Remains open: How to make the Textfields and the Tabfolder as FLAT? Is it worth to open a new Issue? I mean are there changes to get it as well realized? Sufficient to reopen this Bug????
Can't make them flat because there is no support for this in the operating system. On the plus side, when the user changes system colors adn look and feel, your application will behave properly.

Your arguments about the Plus-side applies as well to the Toolbar, but nevertheless the Toolbar has the Option. Why the one, while the others not. And if it is really on OS issue, then I am really suprised. But I see, there are no other otpion in and ...
BUTT, the Toolbar-Items behave strange, especially the drop-down Toolbar-Item.
In the Classic XP-Styple: REGULAR: A Border around the Immage/Text+a Border around the Drop-Down. FLAT: An inconsitent left Border and no Border at all.
In the Enhanced XP-Styple (or however you wanna name it): REGULAR: No Border around the Immage/Text+a Border around the Drop-Down. FLAT: An inconsitent left Border and no Border at all.
I have no idea what good is that inconsitent left Border.
I understand the Drop-Down Marker something like a Button and THEREFORE I would expect to have the Border around it. Arguments are many, like consistent GUI-Design, consitent L&F for the programmer with no idea about the different Themes, etc.etc.
Example where taken from the Plugin-Samples, SWT Controls

> Your arguments about ...
I'm not really arguing anything. The SWT tool bar should look and behave the same as tool bars found in other native applications, for example Wordpad or the Explorer. When the theme is changed to classic, it should look classic. When the theme is changed to XP, then it should look XP. If this is not the case, enter another bug report and put me on it.

The only inconsitency I see is with the drop-down Toolbar-Item. As described above. But frankly said, I have no idea, what the default OS-behaviour should look like, cause e.g. Wordpad use them only as Comboboxes. And therefore ...
If there are no further bits to chew on, then close this ticket.
